00:25:26,910 --> 00:25:29,460
They don't mention their jobs in the article.

252
00:25:29,460 --> 00:25:33,440
The first thing to do in a serial killer investigation is to find out what the victims have in common.

253
00:25:33,440 --> 00:25:37,060
Why are the victims' occupations all missing from the article?

254
00:25:39,030 --> 00:25:40,700
Isn't it odd?

255
00:25:40,700 --> 00:25:43,140
Are there only one or two odd things about this case?

256
00:25:44,200 --> 00:25:49,260
This newspaper article is from the local news section of a 1984 print.

257
00:25:49,260 --> 00:25:52,030
Since it was a serial murder case, you only looked at the local news section, right?

258
00:25:52,030 --> 00:25:55,220
But the information was in the wrong place.

259
00:25:56,230 --> 00:25:58,110
In the economic section.

260
00:25:59,750 --> 00:26:02,560
 Economic News 
 Hanmyeong University and Taesam Chemical collaboration

261
00:26:02,560 --> 00:26:06,250
Professor Park In Sang's Hanmyeong University research team.

262
00:26:06,250 --> 00:26:10,800
Pictured from left to right are researchers Im Sang Wuk and Oh Jong Geun.

263
00:26:10,800 --> 00:26:12,920
University researchers?

264
00:26:12,920 --> 00:26:16,540
It's a development project collaboration between the industry and a graduate research team.

265
00:26:16,540 --> 00:26:18,820
All three people who died were from the same research team.

266
00:26:18,820 --> 00:26:20,770
What project was this?

267
00:26:20,770 --> 00:26:26,000
It was called TH-5. It was a disinfectant developed and patented in 1984.

268
00:26:26,000 --> 00:26:30,130
There has been a lot of talk about it these days because people have died.

269
00:26:30,130 --> 00:26:32,460
TH-5?

270
00:26:33,270 --> 00:26:38,500
These two and this person here are the victims.

271
00:26:38,500 --> 00:26:43,010
This is Taesam Chemical Director Seo Hyeon Tae. He was in charge of product development at the time.

272
00:26:43,010 --> 00:26:45,110
Seo Hyeon Tae.

273
00:26:45,110 --> 00:26:47,010
I feel like I've heard that name a lot somewhere.

274
00:26:47,010 --> 00:26:50,220
You don't know Seoryun Group Chairman Seo Hyeon Tae?

275
00:26:50,220 --> 00:26:53,390
Seoryun? The conglomorate company Seoryun?

276
00:26:53,390 --> 00:26:57,170
Taesam Chemical merged with Seoryun after their successful product development.

277
00:26:57,170 --> 00:27:01,190
And Seo Hyeon Tae married Lee Hwa Jeong, the princess of Seoryun.

278
00:27:04,410 --> 00:27:07,590
You know that suicide case that happened in front of the Seoryun office a little while ago right?

279
00:27:07,590 --> 00:27:11,230
You mean the Evergreen case where the victim committed suicide after asking for compensation, right?

280
00:27:11,230 --> 00:27:14,420
Do you know what the main ingredient of Evergreen is?

281
00:27:14,420 --> 00:27:16,730
TH-5?

282
00:27:21,530 --> 00:27:25,270
Should I tell you something interesting to cool down all the complicated thoughts you're having right now?

283
00:27:27,460 --> 00:27:32,080
Do you know who Lee Hwa Jeong's older brother is?

284
00:27:32,080 --> 00:27:34,320
Who is it?

285
00:27:34,320 --> 00:27:39,850
The prosecutor who spearheaded the investigation into the Chimera case in 1984.

286
00:27:39,850 --> 00:27:42,090
Assemblyman Lee Min Gi.

287
00:27:51,290 --> 00:27:55,420
In this case, you have to end it at once. That's for its sake too.

288
00:27:55,420 --> 00:27:58,720
You did this all yourself?

289
00:27:58,720 --> 00:28:02,900
Your hobbies are really something too. If I were you, I wouldn't do it because I can't be bothered.

290
00:28:02,900 --> 00:28:06,020
Wow.

291
00:28:15,660 --> 00:28:18,650
Rather than carrying a hundred coal briquettes from the village,

292
00:28:18,650 --> 00:28:21,220
taking pictures of cooking and posting them

293
00:28:21,220 --> 00:28:24,480
is much more appealing to voters nowadays.

294
00:28:24,480 --> 00:28:27,530
I should learn how to cook too.

295
00:28:27,530 --> 00:28:31,920
You can't do that. Your dexterity isn't good enough.

296
00:28:38,200 --> 00:28:43,260
Hyeongnim, how is President Lee feeling?

297
00:28:43,260 --> 00:28:45,150
Do you think she'd be happy?

298
00:28:45,820 --> 00:28:49,230
I heard that doctor spent all day waiting to be released.

299
00:28:49,230 --> 00:28:53,870
Oh, well, the others are catching on.

300
00:28:53,870 --> 00:28:56,830
Good going.

301
00:28:56,830 --> 00:29:00,650
Anyway, just bow your head down and definitely beg for forgiveness.

302
00:29:00,650 --> 00:29:02,300
All right.

303
00:29:25,740 --> 00:29:27,660
Here, let's eat.

304
00:29:27,660 --> 00:29:29,950
- You've worked hard. 
 - Thanks.

305
00:29:29,950 --> 00:29:31,760
Have some.

306
00:29:48,820 --> 00:29:51,950
Hyeongsunim, please relax now.

307
00:29:51,950 --> 00:29:56,380
I really committed a sin and deserve to die.   Please have a drink.

308
00:30:08,840 --> 00:30:10,600
Thank you.

309
00:30:15,280 --> 00:30:17,580
Let's drink.

310
00:30:27,480 --> 00:30:33,180
I mean, the guys under me did whatever they wanted at dawn without telling me.

311
00:30:33,180 --> 00:30:37,800
I scolded the investigation team a lot so please don't be too angry.

312
00:30:37,800 --> 00:30:41,560
I heard they made him suffer until he was released at nearly sunset.

313
00:30:41,560 --> 00:30:44,030
Do young kids listen to anyone nowadays?

314
00:30:44,030 --> 00:30:46,920
They are self-centered and do whatever they please.

315
00:30:46,920 --> 00:30:48,790
They are killing me.

316
00:30:48,790 --> 00:30:50,580
Good going.

317
00:30:50,580 --> 00:30:54,300
Which case is it that there is such a fuss?

318
00:30:54,300 --> 00:30:56,580
That's ...

319
00:30:57,400 --> 00:31:01,780
Someone in our department died. It is a murder.

320
00:31:01,780 --> 00:31:05,500
An officer was murdered? Who?

321
00:31:05,500 --> 00:31:08,200
The one on the verge of retirement?  That police officer?

322
00:31:08,200 --> 00:31:13,120
My goodness.  How did he end up being murdered? How was it done?

323
00:31:13,120 --> 00:31:16,280
It's similar to chemical terrorism.

324
00:31:16,280 --> 00:31:20,780
They say the method is unique and something strange was found at the scene.

325
00:31:22,540 --> 00:31:24,700
What was found?

326
00:31:26,940 --> 00:31:29,170
A lighter.

327
00:31:29,970 --> 00:31:31,920
A lighter?

328
00:31:31,920 --> 00:31:36,390
Yes.  Wasn't the same pattern in the chimera case

329
00:31:38,830 --> 00:31:41,890
thirty-five years ago?

330
00:31:48,400 --> 00:31:51,700
What happened? Are you drunk already?

331
00:31:51,700 --> 00:31:54,330
I'm not drunk. I didn't drink that much.

332
00:31:54,330 --> 00:31:58,260
In any case, there are too many things on your mind now.  Please drink in moderation.

333
00:31:58,260 --> 00:32:02,060
When the three of you get together, you think you're young again.

334
00:32:24,680 --> 00:32:29,550
What do you mean by chimera lighter? Tell us the details.

335
00:32:33,090 --> 00:32:37,790
There was a case in 1984 for which Hyeongnim Min Gi led the investigation.

336
00:32:37,790 --> 00:32:40,630
Right after you were assigned to the Ministry of Public Security.

337
00:32:40,630 --> 00:32:44,460
The serial arson murder case in Macheon City.

338
00:32:45,510 --> 00:32:49,090
The name of the culprit was Lee Sang Wu, right?

339
00:32:49,090 --> 00:32:54,420
The MO used in the recent cases is identical.

340
00:32:54,420 --> 00:32:56,980
There were two explosions, and after each, there was someone dead, and

341
00:32:56,980 --> 00:33:00,260
a lighter with a chimera design turned up at the scene.

342
00:33:01,060 --> 00:33:03,820
Who are the people who died?

343
00:33:03,820 --> 00:33:07,970
One was a reporter who covered the Chimera case.

344
00:33:07,970 --> 00:33:12,350
The other was Han Ju Seok. He was a detective who worked on the case at the time.

345
00:33:13,060 --> 00:33:18,270
It's hard to ignore it as just a coincidence.

346
00:33:20,690 --> 00:33:24,320
Couldn't it be a copycat or some similar imitator?

347
00:33:24,320 --> 00:33:26,740
How would he know the MO of a case from 35 years ago?

348
00:33:26,740 --> 00:33:30,990
Both Min Gi, who was the prosecutor in charge, and I don't know.

349
00:33:36,650 --> 00:33:41,360
But, how is that Seoryun doctor involved?

350
00:33:41,360 --> 00:33:45,250
I heard he was caught on the CCTV loitering around the scenes of the incidents.

351
00:33:45,250 --> 00:33:47,760
He hasn't been cleared of suspicion nor charged, but it's not clear.

352
00:33:47,760 --> 00:33:50,240
What kind of person is he? Did you see him?

353
00:33:50,240 --> 00:33:52,820
He looks fine and he's smart.

354
00:33:52,820 --> 00:33:55,300
He is Korean-British.

355
00:33:55,300 --> 00:33:56,880
He's Korean?

356
00:33:56,880 --> 00:33:59,050
Yes, an adopted child.

357
00:33:59,050 --> 00:34:01,190
Adopted child?

358
00:34:01,190 --> 00:34:02,860
His name?

359
00:34:02,860 --> 00:34:06,980
Lee Jung Yeop. Is it a name you know?

360
00:34:06,980 --> 00:34:09,610
Not really, I'm hearing it for the first time.

361
00:34:09,610 --> 00:34:15,740
Hwa Jeong brought him here at great expense.  He couldn't be the culprit.

362
00:34:16,590 --> 00:34:18,690
I guess so.

363
00:34:18,690 --> 00:34:22,090
But something doesn't feel right.

364
00:34:22,090 --> 00:34:27,100
What are you afraid of? What are you worried about?

365
00:34:27,100 --> 00:34:30,280
The Chimera died.

366
00:34:30,280 --> 00:34:33,160
Thirty-five years ago.

367
00:34:42,080 --> 00:34:44,300
The progress looks good.

368
00:34:44,300 --> 00:34:49,200
Because my primary doctor is good looking, I guess the medical treatment is effective.

369
00:34:51,300 --> 00:34:54,110
Don't you have any information

370
00:34:54,110 --> 00:34:57,100
other than the three syllables of the name of the person

371
00:34:57,100 --> 00:34:59,340
you asked me to search for before, Ham Yong Bok?

372
00:34:59,340 --> 00:35:01,980
I think he might be in his 60's now.

373
00:35:01,980 --> 00:35:05,000
He was a government employee at the Macheon police station thirty-five years ago.

374
00:35:05,000 --> 00:35:06,720
A detective?

375
00:35:06,720 --> 00:35:08,740
He's not easy to find, is he?

376
00:35:08,740 --> 00:35:13,620
If he's an ex-detective, I can find him after crossing several bridges.

377
00:35:13,620 --> 00:35:16,440
I may be pointlessly putting you through the trouble.

378
00:35:16,440 --> 00:35:20,510
What do you mean trouble?  It's a chance for me to pay my debt to you.

379
00:35:20,510 --> 00:35:26,600
I'm responsible for your having to suffer being taken to the police station.

380
00:35:27,440 --> 00:35:29,930
I don't blame you.

381
00:35:31,320 --> 00:35:33,850
Jeez.

382
00:35:33,850 --> 00:35:37,860
How can I tell if you're sincere or not?

383
00:35:40,900 --> 00:35:43,440
But who is that person?

384
00:35:46,910 --> 00:35:48,680
Family?

385
00:35:51,840 --> 00:35:53,950
or an enemy?

386
00:35:55,280 --> 00:36:00,240
I just have some questions to ask that person.

387
00:36:07,030 --> 00:36:08,780
Doctor Lee.

388
00:36:09,610 --> 00:36:14,570
As someone who is going to die, can I give you some advice?

389
00:36:14,570 --> 00:36:15,940
It's not a fatal disease.

390
00:36:15,940 --> 00:36:20,010
- If you take your medicine and take good care of yourself—
 - Don't look back at the past.

391
00:36:20,010 --> 00:36:22,350
There's nothing to gain.

392
00:36:24,830 --> 00:36:30,760
You're healthy, handsome and have a great job.

393
00:36:30,760 --> 00:36:33,210
Is it because you're lacking something?

394
00:36:34,200 --> 00:36:39,170
Without regard to age, country, time and place, is there someone who benefitted from turning back to look at the past?

395
00:36:41,960 --> 00:36:43,990
Doctor Lee,

396
00:36:45,020 --> 00:36:50,180
even if you can find your enemy, you can't find your family.

397
00:36:53,100 --> 00:36:55,920
The instant you search, they become an enemy.

398
00:37:04,650 --> 00:37:08,710
Let's say you are sitting and facing a suspect in the interrogation room.

399
00:37:08,710 --> 00:37:11,400
What should you say first?

400
00:37:11,400 --> 00:37:14,920
Option 1.  What's the best memory of your life?

401
00:37:14,920 --> 00:37:17,710
Option 2.  What's your worst memory?

402
00:37:17,710 --> 00:37:21,020
What's your choice between the two questions?

403
00:37:21,870 --> 00:37:24,420
The answer is option 2.

404
00:37:24,420 --> 00:37:28,510
No one answers if I ask about what they enjoyed or liked.

405
00:37:28,510 --> 00:37:30,970
But if you ask about the worst memories,

406
00:37:30,970 --> 00:37:36,250
it's a startling experience in which the adversary suddenly can't utter a word.

407
00:37:36,250 --> 00:37:38,350
I have a question.

408
00:37:42,940 --> 00:37:46,790
There are situations in which an innocent person makes a false confession.

409
00:37:46,790 --> 00:37:49,210
Why is that?

410
00:37:50,710 --> 00:37:53,780
Because of a coercive atmosphere?

411
00:37:53,780 --> 00:37:57,340
Because of physical threats such as torture?

412
00:37:58,360 --> 00:38:00,210
What do you think is the reason?

413
00:38:05,230 --> 00:38:08,880
An innocent person makes a false confession.

414
00:38:11,550 --> 00:38:14,420
Anyone can do that.

415
00:38:14,420 --> 00:38:17,940
They aren't mentally abnormal. Nor is it coerced.

416
00:38:19,040 --> 00:38:22,390
Are you saying a false confession is made even without coercion?

417
00:38:22,390 --> 00:38:26,000
They may be deprived of physical freedom and intensely interrogated about their worries and concerns.

418
00:38:26,000 --> 00:38:30,180
There also may be complex circumstances which may cause harm to their family.

419
00:38:30,180 --> 00:38:32,500
They may not know how long the situation will last.

420
00:38:32,500 --> 00:38:35,450
If that happens, there is overwhelming stress.

421
00:38:35,450 --> 00:38:41,120
So they just want to simply and quickly escape from that situation.

422
00:38:41,200 --> 00:38:45,600
So that person thinks, "let's just give the answer they want."

423
00:38:45,620 --> 00:38:47,710
Is that all of it?

424
00:38:50,790 --> 00:38:55,960
I mean, it's not like they are stupid, what happens when they confess and get punished?

425
00:38:56,660 --> 00:38:58,250
No way.

426
00:38:59,000 --> 00:39:03,900
They think, "when I go to court, the truth will be revealed."

427
00:39:03,920 --> 00:39:07,930
They do not realize how fatal that mistake is.

428
00:39:10,550 --> 00:39:16,010
Things that ordinary people usually cannot imagine happen in the interrogation room.

429
00:39:16,010 --> 00:39:21,060
They are out of touch with reality about the punishment which will be handed out.

430
00:39:21,060 --> 00:39:26,240
Even if it is the court's severest sentence, the death penalty.

431
00:39:35,800 --> 00:39:40,800
Miss Eugene, can we talk briefly?

432
00:39:42,600 --> 00:39:45,740
I don't think there's any reason for us to talk privately.

433
00:39:45,740 --> 00:39:49,360
"Until a final judgment has been rendered, do not interact personally with the defendant."

434
00:39:49,360 --> 00:39:53,410
"You may become biased."  It's a profiler's rule.

435
00:39:53,410 --> 00:39:55,290
You're very knowledgeable.

436
00:39:55,290 --> 00:39:59,620
Then instead of interaction, let's do something else.

437
00:40:01,040 --> 00:40:02,350
Something else?

438
00:40:02,350 --> 00:40:04,620
Do you like chess?

439
00:40:11,440 --> 00:40:14,890
White.  I go first, right?

440
00:40:20,880 --> 00:40:23,110
Aren't you afraid?

441
00:40:23,110 --> 00:40:24,440
Of what?

442
00:40:24,440 --> 00:40:27,120
Being alone with me.

443
00:40:27,120 --> 00:40:30,850
What if I was a real serial killer?

444
00:40:31,740 --> 00:40:36,500
It's an honor. If I write a book later on, it will be a best-seller.

445
00:40:38,670 --> 00:40:41,460
Til what age did you live in Korea?

446
00:40:42,720 --> 00:40:44,650
Seven years old.

447
00:40:45,520 --> 00:40:48,910
That's old enough to remember what you did when you were young.

448
00:40:48,910 --> 00:40:51,850
Such as about your parents here.

449
00:40:55,950 --> 00:40:58,270
They are dead.

450
00:40:59,420 --> 00:41:02,280
I found my mother's body.  (  In English )

451
00:41:08,680 --> 00:41:10,980
What about your father. (  In English )

452
00:41:11,660 --> 00:41:15,160
Where was he when your mother died?  (  In English )

453
00:41:15,160 --> 00:41:17,120
He was killed.  (  In English )

454
00:41:26,940 --> 00:41:29,670
What happened?

